                <section class ="secondhand" id="secondhand">
                    <h2>Second Hand, Second  Love</h2>
                    <p>Usage condition grading terminology:</p>
                    <ol id="grading-list">
                        <li><i>M </i><strong>(mint)</strong> - Absolutely <b>perfect</b> in every way. <b>Never</b> been played and usually <b>sealed</b>. Often rumored but rarely seen, Mint should never be used as a grade unless more than one person agrees that the record or sleeve truly is in this condition.</li>
                            
                        <li><i>NM </i><strong>(near mint)</strong> - The record looks like it's been opened for the <b>first</b> time. <b>Glossy</b> disc which clearly has only been played a <b>few</b> times. There are <b>no</b> marks on it and the whole package is <b>complete</b>.</li>
                            
                        <li><i>VG </i><strong>(very good)</strong> - More <b>obvious flaws</b>, but still usable. A little rub, light visible scratches or marks, a seam split. When played, it has <em>surface noise</em>, and some scratches may be audible, especially in soft passages and during a song's intro and ending. But the noise will not overpower the music otherwise.</li>
                            
                        <li><i>G </i><strong>(good)</strong> - Good does <b>not</b> mean <b>bad</b>! The record still plays through without skipping, so it can serve as a filler song until something better comes along. But it has <b>significant</b> <em>surface noise</em> and <em>groove wear</em>.</li>
                            
                        <li><i>F </i><strong>(fair)</strong> - Expect <b>major</b> noise <b>issues</b>, <em>skipping</em> or <em>repeating</em>. The record is cracked, warped and have <b>deep scratches</b>. The cover are also <b>wrecked</b>. Only the most outrageously rare items ever sell for more than a few cents in this condition.</li>
                    </ol>
