                    <h3>Trivia: How to calculate the surface of a disc?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Generally, there are 2 types of vinyl records: <i>33 RPM</i> and <i>45 RPM</i>. Their dimensions are 18 cm and 30 cm respectively. These lengths correspond to the <i>diametral length of a circle</i> (D), which helps us to calculate the <i>radius</i>: <br> <br>
                        <div class="math">
                            <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                                <mrow class="radius-formula">
                                    <mi>R</mi>
                                    <mo>=</mo>
                                    <mfrac>
                                        <mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow>
                                        <mrow><mi>2</mi></mrow> 
                                    </mfrac>
                                </mrow>
                            </math>
                        </div>
                        
                        <br> <br>The formula for <i>area of a circle</i> is: <br> <br>
                        <div class="math">
                            <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                                <mrow class="area-formula">
                                    <mi>A</mi> 
                                    <mo>=</mo>
                                    <mi>&#960;</mi>
                                    <mo>Ã—</mo>
                                    <msup> 
                                        <mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow>
                                        <mrow><mi>2</mi></mrow> 
                                    </msup>
                                </mrow>
                            </math>
                        </div>
                        
                        <br> <br>Just replace <span>&#960;</span> with its approximate value (3.14159...) and there you have it, the surface of a vinyl disc!   
                    </p>
